						<h3>Conventional Farming</h3>
						<div class="row">
							<div class="col-md-12" style="padding:0 30px">
								<p>
									Conventional Farming in India is still at a developing stage with only 528,171 hectare area
									covered under Conventional cultivation. The sectors opening up with more organisations and 
									NGO’s catering to farm level activities to consolidate farmers into Conventional farming and 
									selling the products through their stores and network, further carrying huge export 
									potential. Rising awareness of healthy food apart from increased disposable income has 
									ensured nearly 62% of households in the upper end segments preferring to have Conventional 
									products. 
								</p>
								<p>
									The value chain remains fragmented and dispersed with no vision towards integration and
									inclusiveness of farmers and farmer’s allied produce into the value chain. Onus is on 
									export and retail penetration with sparse  recognition to farmer and his contribution, 
									thus deals based on certificate with minimum traceability and accountability. Lack of 
									proper customer education on Conventional products, thus most preference still on fruits and 
									vegetables with promising growth in other segments. Need for an organization that would 
									ensure inclusive growth of the farmer and take his product on an international arena.
								</p>
								<p>
									In India, certified Conventional farming accounts to only 1% of the overall agriculture 
									production . However Conventional farming is still small worldwide and it accounts for less 
									than 2% of the global retail production. India though being 13th in Conventional land under 
									cultivation has most number of producers in Conventional farming 400’551 followed by Uganda 
									188’625, and Mexico 128’862. It is estimated that 65 per cent of the country’s cropped 
									area is Conventional by default, as small farmers (less than 3 acres holding) have no choice 
									but to farm without chemical fertilisers and pesticides which they cannot afford.
									Usage of fertilizers and pesticides have depleted the soil, and inefficient irrigation 
									have caused water tables to plunge in many parts of India.
								</p>
								<p>
									Biodiversity and ecological intensification are the basic premise why more farmers are 
									being fascinated to Conventional farming as this reason has seen a CAGR 20% increase in 
									Conventional cultivation YoY. Apart from Rajasthan other states doing well in Conventional farming 
									are Madhya Pradesh (4.40 lakh hectare), Maharashtra (1.50 lakh hectare) and Orissa 
									(95,000 hectare).
								</p>
							</div>
